                    <span>This book was really good. It made me want to keep on reading it and not set it down. The author describes the characters very well, and makes them very realistic. The book takes you to that world and you get lost in the book.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Alex's review</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>4</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>4</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-24</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>This book was okay. There was a lot of adventure and it was suspenseful. I liked how they used Icelandic language when the Northmen talked. 
<br />	Jack, a Saxon boy, is the son of a farmer, a farm brat, nothing special. Then one day the Bard of the village asks him if he wants to be his apprentice. Everything is great, Jack learns about the life force, simple magic, and animals but then from across the sea Queen Frith sends Bard a Nightmare. Queen Frith is half human half troll and is married to King Ivar the Boneless. The Bard acts like a baby and Jack doesn't know what to do.  Northmen then attack the village kidnapping Jack and his sister Lucy.  Thorgil owns Lucy; a berserker wanna be who is fierce. Olaf One Brow owns Jack, the captain of the ship. When Olaf finds that Jack is the apprentice of the Bard they were supposed to make sure was dead, he brings him to Queen Frith. When Frith sees Jack he is Olaf's personal skald who sings songs of praise. As greedy as she is Frith wants a praise song too. Jack sings about how pretty her hair is and it falls out. Not having the knowledge to undo the spell Jack, Olaf , and Thorgil journey to Jotunheim, troll country, to find Mimir's Well. While fighting against a troll bear Olaf dies leaving Jack and Thorgil to continue by themselves.  Then they meet a couple of nine-foot trolls with orange hair and they show them to their palace to meet the Queen. The queen hosts a chess game so they can meet the Norns who control time and fate. These creatures decide they can go to Mimir's well. To drink from Mimir's well you must give something of extreme value up. Jack gives up the Rune of Protection and Thorgil gives up her will to die. On the way to Middle Earth the battle dragons and giant spider and other huge monsters. Jack knows how to get Frith's hair back but Frith being greedy doesn't do everything Jack says. This causes Frith to go mad and run off a cliff. Jack and Lucy go home but nobody really believes what they did, except for the Bard who had transformed into a crow and traveled with them. 
<br />	If you like fantasy and adventure books then you will like to read this book. Also if you like a book where bad things happen you would like this book.
<br /></span>
                  
              
